tance into Alternatives -- t13. Social Democracy and Social Pacts: Austerity Alliances and Their Consequences -- t14. Austerity and Political Crisis: The Radical Left, the Far Right, and Europe’s New Authoritarian Order -- t15. Conclusion -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBryan M. Evans, Stephen McBride, and their contributors delve further into the more practical, ground-level side of the austerity equation in Austerity: The Lived Experience. Economically, austerity policies cannot be seen to work in the way elite interests claim that they do. Rather than soften the blow of the economic and financial crisis of 2008 for ordinary citizens, policies of austerity slow growth and lead to increased inequality. While political consent for such policies may have been achieved, it was reached amidst significant levels of disaffection and strong opposition to the extremes of austerity. The authors build their analysis in three sections, looking alternatively at theoretical and ideological dimensions of the lived experience of austerity; how austerity plays out in various public sector occupations and policy domains; and the class dimensions of austerity. The result is a ground-breaking contribution to the study of austerity politics and policies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEconomic policy. 0aEquality. 0aFinancial crises. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aBaines, Donna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrass, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurron, Neil A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Brya